A screenshot from Discord Research. It asks:

"In general, how do you feel about Discord integrating AI features? We'd love to hear your overall thoughts and any concerns you might have."

And I answer:

"I don't see the need. I use a ton of programs that have introduced AI features and in all cases I either ignore them (if they can't be disabled) or turn them off entirely when possible. If they are obnoxious and constantly shoving themselves in my face, I stop using the product. The only exception is Github Copilot for code autocomplete, which I use in my day job because I'm required to by my employer. In general, I don't trust LLM output, so I won't use it for anything involving research, and I am morally opposed to using it for any creative output (writing, art, music, etc) for a variety of reasons, including that there are no current generative AI products not trained on stolen property. I don't use it for summarization, either, because I'm not a child or an idiot and can understand what I'm reading without simplification. I also believe the companies currently providing it are doing so at a massive loss, fed on wildly speculative VC dollars that are eventually going to dry up, causing a huge economic recession in the process. When you add in the environmental concerns on top of all that, it's a no-brainer to just not use the tech."

Day One entry from Feb 1, 2023:

“The world looks really crazy to me right now, because I see something coming that nobody is reacting to yet.
Sometime in the next few months, we're going to see the first pure software agents that sit in GitHub repos. You'll be able to assign them issues, and they'll produce PRs. At first they'll need a ton of babysitting in code review, but then again, so do early career human engineers.
Less than a year after this, "entry-level software engineer" will cease to be a job at most companies.

Most small software teams will start to rely on GitHub's agents for a little extra capacity instead of hiring more full-time engineers. Some will take this to an extreme, spinning fleets of agents up and down as needed (something that simply cannot be done with human engineers).
At the same time, the agents will be retraining on everyone's code review comments. Their PRs will improve shockingly quickly.”

Same post, continued:

“I watched this happen with Copilot, which was totally unusable in beta and now, less than a year later, probably writes more than half my code by volume. I didn't have to spend any time learning to use it. I just left it on, and it silently made itself more and more useful until it was indispensable.

In 2-3 years, anyone whose job is fundamentally
"turn English into code" (and I'm absolutely counting engineering managers in this) will be in danger. We are incredibly expensive, we're spiky in output, we require meals and sleep and healthcare and motivation. Copilot is $10/ month. By this point, Al agents will be ingesting and operating on entire codebases.
I think in the limit, software that does anything you can describe will be instantly available and free. It's about to be a weird world out there.”
